        <td>Choose plain yogurt and add a drizzle of honey for sweetness.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h2>Tips for Packing Gluten-Free Lunches</h2>

<p>Packing a gluten-free lunch requires a bit of extra planning, but these tips can make the process easier:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Read Labels Carefully:</strong> Many processed foods contain hidden gluten. Always check the ingredient list and look for certified gluten-free labels.</li>
    <li><strong>Use Separate Utensils:</strong> To avoid cross-contamination, use separate cutting boards, knives, and containers for gluten-free foods.</li>
    <li><strong>Involve Your Child:</strong> Let your child help choose their lunch items. They’re more likely to eat something they’ve had a hand in selecting.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep It Fresh:</strong> Use insulated lunch bags and ice packs to keep perishable items fresh until lunchtime.</li>
</ul>

<h2>FAQs</h2>

<div class="faq">
    <h3>1. What are some gluten-free alternatives to bread?</h3>
    <p>Gluten-free bread options include those made from rice, quinoa, almond flour, or tapioca starch. You can also use gluten-free wraps, lettuce leaves, or rice cakes as alternatives.</p>

    <h3>2. How can I ensure my child’s lunch is free from cross-contamination?</h3>
    <p>Use separate utensils and containers for gluten-free foods, and clean surfaces thoroughly before preparing meals. Pack lunches in containers that are clearly labeled as gluten-free.</p>

    <h3>3. Are there gluten-free versions of popular snacks?</h3>
    <p>Yes, many brands offer gluten-free versions of popular snacks like crackers, cookies, and pretzels. Always check the packaging for a gluten-free certification.</p>

    <h3>4. Can I make gluten-free lunches ahead of time?</h3>
    <p>Absolutely! Many gluten-free meals can be prepared in advance and stored in the fridge or freezer. Just be sure to pack them in airtight containers to maintain freshness.</p>
</div>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>Packing a gluten-free school lunch for picky eaters doesn’t have to be stressful. With a little creativity and planning, you can provide your child with a variety of delicious and nutritious options that they’ll look forward to eating. By incorporating a mix of proteins, fruits, vegetables, and gluten-free grains, you can ensure your child gets the energy and nutrients they need to thrive at school. Remember to involve your child in the process and keep an eye out for new gluten-free products to keep their lunches exciting and enjoyable.</p>

